<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-10-05T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-10-05T02:00:00-05:00" n="427" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d427">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1163 Am 3/237: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-10-05T15:00:00+08:00">October 5, 1937—3
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received October 5—12:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>760. Your [<hi rend="italic">Shanghai’s</hi>] 738, September 20, 11 p.m.
                            Commander-in-Chief’s 0019–2015<note n="86" xml:id="d427fn86">September
                                19, 8:15 p.m., <ref target="#pg_341">p. 341</ref>.</note> and
                            Department’s 263 [<hi rend="italic">261</hi>] September 24, 1 p.m., to
                            Nanking. Foreign Office replying to Embassy protest of September <pb facs="0373" n="365" xml:id="pg_365"/> 21 denies that Chinese Air
                            Force dropped bombs in Pootung on 18th but states instructions have
                            again been issued to various forces to pay strict attention to foreign
                            property in Shanghai.</p>
                        <p>Sent to Shanghai, repeated to Department.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>